<section id="architecture" class="govuk-!-margin-bottom-8">
  <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">Architecture Overview</h2>

  <p class="govuk-body">
    Simply Readable is a fully serverless application. There are no EC2 instances, no containers,
    and no servers to patch or maintain. The entire stack scales automatically from zero to thousands
    of concurrent document translations, and you only pay for what you use.
  </p>

  <p class="govuk-body">
    The architecture follows an <strong>event-driven pattern</strong>: user actions create records in
    DynamoDB, which trigger Step Functions workflows via EventBridge Pipes. This decouples the user
    interface from the processing backend, enabling reliable, scalable document processing.
  </p>
</section>

<section id="services" class="govuk-!-margin-bottom-8">
  <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">AWS Services</h2>

  <div class="ndx-service-cards">
    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">Amazon Translate</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Neural machine translation supporting 75+ languages. Handles document-level translation preserving formatting. Supports custom terminology for council-specific terms.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">Amazon Bedrock</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Foundation model API providing access to Anthropic Claude. Used for Easy Read text simplification via the Converse API. The model rewrites complex text into short, clear sentences.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">Amazon Comprehend</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Natural language processing for automatic source language detection. Identifies the language of uploaded documents without user input.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">Amazon Cognito</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">User authentication and authorisation. User Pool manages admin accounts with MFA-ready password policies. Identity Pool provides scoped AWS credentials for S3 and Translate access.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">AWS AppSync</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Managed GraphQL API with real-time subscriptions. Provides the data layer between the React frontend and DynamoDB backend. Supports offline operation and optimistic UI updates.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">AWS Step Functions</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Serverless workflow orchestration. Manages multi-step translation and Easy Read pipelines with built-in error handling, retries, and parallel execution.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">AWS Lambda</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Serverless compute for individual processing tasks: document parsing, DynamoDB stream unmarshalling, Bedrock invocation, and S3 operations.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">Amazon DynamoDB</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Serverless NoSQL database for job tracking and metadata. DynamoDB Streams enable event-driven processing. Pay-per-request billing with point-in-time recovery.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">Amazon S3</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Object storage for uploaded documents, translated outputs, and the React web application. Identity-scoped paths ensure users can only access their own files.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">Amazon CloudFront</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Global content delivery network serving the React web application. TLS 1.2+ encryption, SPA routing via custom error pages.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="ndx-service-card">
      <h3 class="govuk-heading-s">AWS WAF</h3>
      <p class="govuk-body-s">Web Application Firewall protecting the AppSync API with AWS Managed Rules (Common Rule Set). Blocks common web exploits and bot traffic.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section id="translation-flow" class="govuk-!-margin-bottom-8">
  <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">Document Translation Flow</h2>

  <ol class="govuk-list govuk-list--number govuk-list--spaced">
    <li><strong>Upload:</strong> User uploads a document via the React app. The file is stored in S3 under a Cognito identity-scoped path (<code>private/{identity-id}/...</code>).</li>
    <li><strong>Job creation:</strong> The app creates a translation job record in DynamoDB via AppSync GraphQL mutation.</li>
    <li><strong>Event trigger:</strong> DynamoDB Streams captures the new record. EventBridge Pipes filters for translation job events and starts a Step Functions workflow.</li>
    <li><strong>Translation:</strong> Step Functions calls Amazon Translate for each target language. For short documents, this uses real-time translation. For longer documents, it uses asynchronous batch translation with a callback pattern.</li>
    <li><strong>Storage:</strong> Translated files are written back to S3 alongside the original document.</li>
    <li><strong>Notification:</strong> Job status is updated in DynamoDB. AppSync subscriptions notify the frontend in real-time, updating the UI without page refresh.</li>
  </ol>
</section>

<section id="readable-flow" class="govuk-!-margin-bottom-8">
  <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">Easy Read Flow</h2>

  <ol class="govuk-list govuk-list--number govuk-list--spaced">
    <li><strong>Upload:</strong> User uploads a .docx file to the Simply Readable section.</li>
    <li><strong>Document parsing:</strong> A Lambda function converts the .docx to HTML, then splits it into individual paragraphs.</li>
    <li><strong>Paragraph storage:</strong> Each paragraph is saved as a separate DynamoDB item with status "generate".</li>
    <li><strong>Event trigger:</strong> DynamoDB Streams + EventBridge Pipes detect items with status "generate" and start a Step Functions workflow for each paragraph.</li>
    <li><strong>AI simplification:</strong> Step Functions invokes Amazon Bedrock (Claude) via the Converse API with a prompt instructing it to simplify the text into Easy Read format.</li>
    <li><strong>Result storage:</strong> The simplified text is saved back to DynamoDB with status "completed".</li>
    <li><strong>Display:</strong> The frontend displays original and simplified text side by side via AppSync queries.</li>
  </ol>
</section>

<section id="security" class="govuk-!-margin-bottom-8">
  <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">Security</h2>

  <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet govuk-list--spaced">
    <li><strong>Authentication:</strong> Cognito User Pool with enforced advanced security mode, strong password policy, no self-signup</li>
    <li><strong>Authorisation:</strong> Identity Pool issues scoped AWS credentials. Users can only access their own S3 paths.</li>
    <li><strong>API protection:</strong> AWS WAF with Managed Rules protects the AppSync endpoint</li>
    <li><strong>Encryption:</strong> AES-256 at rest (S3, DynamoDB), TLS 1.2+ in transit</li>
    <li><strong>Data isolation:</strong> Each user's documents are stored in identity-scoped S3 paths, enforced by IAM policy conditions</li>
    <li><strong>No data retention:</strong> Amazon Translate and Bedrock do not store input/output data for model training</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section id="costs" class="govuk-!-margin-bottom-8">
  <h2 class="govuk-heading-l">Cost Overview</h2>

  <p class="govuk-body">
    This is a fully serverless architecture with pay-per-use pricing. Costs scale linearly
    with usage, and there are no minimum charges for most services.
  </p>

  <table class="govuk-table">
    <thead class="govuk-table__head">
      <tr class="govuk-table__row">
        <th class="govuk-table__header" scope="col">Service</th>
        <th class="govuk-table__header" scope="col">Pricing model</th>
        <th class="govuk-table__header" scope="col">Typical cost</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody class="govuk-table__body">
      <tr class="govuk-table__row">
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">Amazon Translate</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">Per character translated</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">~$15/million characters</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="govuk-table__row">
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">Amazon Bedrock (Claude)</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">Per input/output token</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">~$0.003/1K input tokens</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="govuk-table__row">
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">DynamoDB</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">Per read/write request</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">~$1.25/million writes</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="govuk-table__row">
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">Lambda</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">Per request + duration</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">~$0.20/million requests</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="govuk-table__row">
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">CloudFront</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">Per request + data transfer</td>
        <td class="govuk-table__cell">~$0.085/GB</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="govuk-inset-text">
    <p class="govuk-body govuk-!-margin-bottom-0">
